<chapter xml:id="ch-6-distribution-of-primes" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Arithmetic Functions II</title>
  
  <introduction>
  <p>
  Recall that the von Mangoldt function <m>\Lambda</m> is defined by
  <m>\Lambda(n) = \log p</m> if <m>n = p^k</m> is a power of a prime
  (<m>p</m> prime, <m>k \geq 1</m>), <m>\Lambda(n) = 0</m> otherwise
  (in particular, <m>\Lambda(1) = 1</m>).
  We consider the following three functions:
  <men>
    \pi(x) = \sum_{p \leq x} 1,
    \qquad
    \theta(x) = \sum_{p \leq x} \log p,
    \qquad
    \psi(x) = \sum_{n \leq x} \Lambda(n)
  </men>.
  Here <m>\pi</m> is the prime-counting function,
  <m>\theta</m> is called Chebyshev's <m>\theta</m> function,
  and <m>\psi</m> is called Chebyshev's <m>\psi</m> function.
  </p>
  
  </introduction>

